PORT: interpretation biases variance

Thomas McGregor

2023-05-22

Setup

Cleaning

Subsets

Brief

Colette and I are just discussing the design of the study in the new grant and mulling on the impact of selecting participants with GAD7 >=8 for variance in worry, interpretation biases etc.

In order to get a sense of this I wondered if one of you could pull out means and SDs for worry, anxiety sensitivity, EACS, CBAS and SST (if it has been coded/cleaned) so we can see how much variance there is in this type of selected sample. It would also be useful to see the correlations between all of these variables and GAD7 scores so we can see if the reduced variance has any impact on associations we’d expect to see.

List of measures

  • GAD 7

  • PHQ9

  • WSAS

  • STAI-T

  • FSS

  • PMH-Scale

  • PSWQ

  • ASI

  • CBAS

  • EACS

  • IUS-12

  • BIS/BAS

  • EPQ-R Nscale

Notes

  • SST is not clean and therefore not available for analyses

GAD-7 scores over time

Graphic illustrating that over time (screening to baseline) and after treatment a greater number of participants fell below the IAPT GAD-7 cut-off for anxiety (>= 8).

Also, from a quick look, at screening there seems to be a few more participants that were eventually excluded that fell below 8 on the GAD-7. However, it’s only around 20 participants, so I will keep them in.

I will produce descriptives and run correlations on the baseline timepoint as it is closest to the measurement of interpretation biases. But it is worth noting that not all participants are 8 and above by this point.
